msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:97
msgid ""
"Physical access to data processing equipment may be performed only by the"
" Flying Circus' :ref:`administrators <administrators>`. Administrators "
"may delegate physical access to other persons (e.g., data center staff)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:101
msgid "Low-security locations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:103
msgid ""
"The Flying Circus operates two low-security zones called `development` "
"(used for the development of the Flying Circus infrastructure) and `WHQ` "
"(used to as staging environment for platform changes, and to operate non "
"critical internal applications)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:106
msgid ""
"Those locations are currently not allowed to be used for customer data "
"storage as they are not sufficiently protected."
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:109
msgid ""
"Due to this limitations, the services in high-security locations are not "
"allowed to depend on services provided in low-security locations."
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:115
msgid "Entry control"
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:117
msgid ""
"**Measures for entry control ensure that unauthorized third parties can "
"not make use of the data processing systems.**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:122
msgid ""
"Machines managed within the Flying Circus can be accessed by a variety of"
" ways for management purposes: SSH, web interfaces, and others. For those"
" we employ a homogeneous scheme to identify and authorize users within "
"the Flying Circus. Management access to systems must use encrypted "
"communication channels."
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:127
msgid ""
"Identification and authorization of customer applications, not managed by"
" the Flying Circus infrastructure, are not covered by our security "
"responsibility. Our customers are required to ensure the security of "
"their applications themselves."
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:130
msgid ""
"User identification must be performed using *personal* credentials, so "
"that actions can be traced back to an individual originator. Thus, "
"sharing one's credentials with another person is prohibited.  Credentials"
" can be either a username and a cryptographic measure (e.g. a "
"private/public key scheme) or a password, depending on the applicability."
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:136
msgid ""
"Users with a Flying Circus account are required to manage their password "
"securely: Passwords must not be compromised if a device is being accessed"
" unauthorizedly (logically or physically). Things to consider are for "
"example: Home directory on a notebook, keychain or password manager "
"software, backups, USB sticks, smartphones. Strongly encrypted storage of"
" passwords is permitted and even advised. For Flying Circus staff there "
"is a separate *guideline for handling secret authentication information*."
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:138
msgid ""
"All hardware machines have emergency root logins which may only be used "
"by :ref:`Flying Circus administrators <administrators>` if regular user "
"authentication is not working correctly. Such uses must be documented."
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:142
msgid ""
"All privileged actions need to be securely logged. For machines based on "
"our current (NixOS) platform, this is achieved via a local logging "
"journal, which cannot be tampered with by normal users. Additionally "
"systems logs are shipped to a central log server within the same site "
"where the logs are analysed and monitored."
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:144
msgid ""
"SSH logins must be performed using SSH keys. Password authentication is "
"not allowed and prevented by the system configuration. Successful SSH "
"logins to machines are logged, unsuccessful SSH login attempts are not "
"[#log-unsuccessful-attempts]_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:150
msgid "Access control"
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:154
msgid ""
"**Measures for access control protect against access by unauthorized "
"personnel.**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:157
msgid ""
"Customer-owned virtual machines may be accessed by all Flying Circus "
":ref:`administrators <administrators>` implicitly. In projects additional"
" staff (e.g. support staff) may get explicit access. Access by others "
"(e.g., customer personnel, third parties) must be authorised by a client "
"representative."
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:163
msgid ""
"Users are centrally managed using https://my.flyingcircus.io. Users are "
"automatically provisioned to all relevant systems, including proper "
"removal of access rights."
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:165
msgid ""
"Flying Circus implements a permission-based concept to separate "
"application maintenance tasks from privileged administrative tasks: for "
"example, customer software updates or database access versus OS updates "
"or OS configuration."
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:169
msgid ""
"Privileged administrative access is generally not granted to customers. "
"In cases where another person who is not an administrator is needed to "
"solve a problem, a shared session between an administrator and the other "
"person must be established (e.g. with :command:`screen`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:175
msgid ""
"Technically, there are three access variants to perform privileged "
"administrative operations:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:178
msgid ""
"Using a user account which has been granted the 'login' and 'wheel' "
":ref:`permissions <permissions>` for a certain project. This requires the"
" user to log into a regular account using his SSH key and additionally "
"provide his password to access privileged operations."
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:183
msgid ""
"Using a user account which is member of the global group of "
"administrators (see :ref:`administrators`) which grants access to all "
"machines within the Flying Circus infrastructure."
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:187
msgid "Emergency root logins (see above in :ref:`entry-control`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:189
msgid ""
"Authorized and unauthorized access to privileged operations is logged and"
" analysed on a central loghost within the same site. [#trace-tty]_"
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:192
msgid ""
"Flying Circus maintains a set of permissions which enable users to "
"perform application maintenance and other semi-privileged tasks, e.g. "
"access to service user accounts or database administration rights. "
"Permissions are granted to individual users by the customer or upon "
"customer request."
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:197
msgid ""
"All permission assignments are traceable and explicitly documented: their"
" effects are documented in the configuration code and their assignments "
"are documented in the configuration database. A comprehensive list of "
"users and their permissions may be produced automatically on request."
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:202
msgid ""
"Group accounts are generally not allowed to perform privileged "
"administrative operations to ensure traceability of actions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:205
msgid ""
"Passwords for physical machines granting access to root accounts and IPMI"
" controllers are stored as copies in a strongly encrypted password "
"manager."
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:210
msgid "Separation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:212
msgid ""
"**Measures for separation ensure that data that is collected for separate"
" purposes must be processed separately.**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:215
msgid ""
"To separate data from different customers the Flying Circus facilitates "
"virtualization: both virtual machines (to separate execution context) and"
" SAN (to separate storage) ensure that customers can only access data "
"belonging to them. Within a single machine access to different files and "
"processes is available using standard UNIX permissions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:221
msgid ""
"Machines (both virtual and physical) live in a specific *access ring* "
"(short: ring):"
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:224
msgid ""
"*Ring 0* machines perform infrastructure tasks. Thus, they need to "
"process data belonging to several customers.  Only administrator access "
"is allowed on such machines.  Examples include VM hosts and storage "
"servers."
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:227
msgid ""
"*Ring 1* machines process data for a specific customer and are accessible"
" to users associated to that customer. Examples include customer VMs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:230
msgid ""
"All resources that belong logically together (e.g., VMs, storage volumes)"
" are bundled into *projects*. projects share that same set of user "
"accounts and permissions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:236
msgid "Pseudonymisation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:238
msgid ""
"**Measures to ensure that personal data can no longer be attributed to a "
"specific person without the use of additional information.**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:240
msgid ""
"We delete data after the retention times required by tax or commercial "
"law."
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:241
msgid "Access log files are being anonymised."
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:242
msgid "We delete customer data upon customer's request."
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:246
msgid "Integrity and Authenticity"
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:249
msgid "Transfer control"
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:253
msgid ""
"**Measures for transfer control ensure that data that is being saved or "
"transferred is protected against unauthorized reading, copying, "
"modification, or deletion. It also requires that the points for "
"intentional transfer are documented.**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:258
msgid ""
"All private data transferred past the boundary of a machine must use an "
"authenticated and encrypted communication channel (exceptions see below)."
" Data paths where sensitive information may be transferred include:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:262
msgid ""
"Application data (e.g., database contents) is transferred from or to the "
"customer using the standardised encrypted protocols, e.g., SCP/SFTP, "
"https."
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:265
msgid ""
"Persistent data is saved on storage servers. Storage traffic is not "
"encrypted due to performance reasons. Storage servers are connected to "
"application servers using a private network. Machines on which "
"administrative privileges are granted to customers are not allowed to "
"connect directly to the storage network (see also :ref:`network-"
"security`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:271
msgid ""
"Backups are transferred to backup servers at the same site using either "
"an encrypted communication channel or the private storage network. Backup"
" data may also be transferred to off-site backup servers to improve "
"disaster recovery abilities."
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:275
msgid ""
"In addition to application data, a system can generate data at runtime "
"that contains sensitive information, for example log files. Log files "
"usually do not leave the machine on which they were generated, unless the"
" customer operates a logging server. Log data may also be transferred to "
"a log server on the same site operated by Flying Circus via an encrypted "
"channel. Only Flying Circus administrators may have access to the central"
" log server."
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:282
msgid "Input control"
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:284
msgid ""
"**Measures for input control ensure that input, change, and deletion of "
"data are documented showing at least who worked when on what data.**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:287
msgid ""
"The security of data entry, change and deletion is generally part of the "
"customer's application. Customers must ensure that data entry, deletion "
"and removal are handled appropriately according to their applicable data "
"protection laws."
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:292
msgid ""
"However, during maintenance work it may be necessary that administrators "
"need to enter, change, or delete data records on a low technical level to"
" ensure the continued operation of the overall system. This will only "
"happen after having informed the affected customers and having documented"
" this in our issue tracking system."
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:298
msgid ""
"Managed log files are rotated by the Flying Circus infrastructure "
"automatically with sensible retention times."
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:301
msgid ""
"Changes in the Flying Circus user directory (e.g., SSH keys) can be "
"performed by the customer themselves or through our support. If the "
"change happens through our support then it must be documented beforehand "
"and confirmed by the customer after the change has been performed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:308
msgid "Order control"
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:310
msgid ""
"**Measures for order control ensure that data is only processed according"
" to the orders of the client.**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:313
msgid ""
"The Flying Circus ensures that all actions taken by system administrators"
" are covered by a contract or order with the customers affected by the "
"action. This can be due to broad maintenance contracts or due to specific"
" support requests."
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:317
msgid ""
"Individual change requests should have an associated ticket in the Flying"
" Circus request tracking system. Other means of documentation to control "
"changes are possible, e.g., explanatory commit messages in a version "
"control system."
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:320
msgid "Specific actions performed will be reported to the customer if required."
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:324
msgid "Availability"
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:326
msgid ""
"**Measures for availability ensure that data is not accidentally "
"destroyed or lost.**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:329
msgid ""
"The availability of resources depending on the data center facilities is "
"delegated to the operator of the data center. The Flying Circus "
"facilitates service level agreements to make expectations about "
"availability explicit."
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:333
msgid ""
"The selection of hardware is performed by the Flying Circus using "
"professional equipment and vendors. The Flying Circus facilitates "
"standard procedures for increased availability of single components "
"(e.g., RAID storages, redundant power supplies, spare components)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:338
msgid ""
"Customer data is regularly backed up according to the Flying Circus' "
":ref:`backup schedule <backup>`. Restoration of past states may be "
"performed by administrators on request. Additionally, a :ref:`disaster "
"recovery plan <disaster-recovery>` details failure scenarios, our "
"preventative and recovery measures."
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:347
msgid "Other measures"
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:349
msgid ""
"Our support process and incident response measures are documented at "
":ref:`the support overview <support-details>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:350
msgid ""
"We have a process for emergency and crisis management including "
"contingency plans for critical business processes (business continuity). "
"See also :ref:`disaster-recovery`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:354
msgid "Footnotes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:355
msgid ""
"If a customer owns equipment managed within the Flying Circus we require "
"that this customer uses a separate rack with separate access control."
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:358
msgid ""
"We consider not logging unsuccessful logins acceptable, as SSH logins are"
" only valid using cryptographic private/public key authentication. "
"Password logins are always rejected. Potential attack vectors are thus "
"limited to stolen or cracked private keys or vulnerabilities in the SSH "
"server software. Cracked keys are practically impossible using current "
"technology. Known broken key formats are revoked/rejected regularly. "
"Stolen keys or errors in the server software will not be traceable using "
"unsuccessful login records either.  On the opposite: the amount of "
"password login tries performed nowadays (due to bot nets etc.) would "
"cause spamming of the logging infrastructure which in turn can be a "
"vector for DOS attacks."
msgstr ""

#: ../../src/reference/security/data-protection.rst:370
msgid ""
"Individual actions performed with administrative privileges are only "
"partially logged."
msgstr ""

